ens\":4237,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":75862,\"output_tokens\":710,\"server_tool_use\":{\"web_search_requests\":0,\"web_fetch_requests\":0},\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":4237,\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0},\"inference_geo\":\"\",\"iterations\":[],\"speed\":\"standard\"}},\"sourceToolAssistantUUID\":\"e3c98e5c-73c2-4984-86d4-03d706b0fd6d\"}\n{\"parentUuid\":\"cf3d8b63-72b8-42ad-b7ba-96eb854caa89\",\"isSidechain\":false,\"userType\":\"external\",\"cwd\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli\",\"sessionId\":\"107bbb07-3754-4cb3-b825-212f7c3591bc\",\"version\":\"2.1.63\",\"gitBranch\":\"feat/trails\",\"slug\":\"warm-brewing-fog\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"assistant\",\"timestamp\":\"2026-03-03T14:44:59.242Z\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"claude-opus-4-6\",\"id\":\"msg_01VdAqpNqq9R8DtWRCfXsiZR\",\"type\":\"message\",\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"toolu_011MmKmBM7GXjrmtV9qQNR5W\",\"name\":\"Write\",\"input\":{\"file_path\":\"/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/docs/requirements/trails/review-02.md\",\"content\":\"# Review 02 -- Efficiency Analysis of trail.Store Refactoring\\n\\n> Status: pending-dev\\n> Date: 2026-03-03\\n> Reviewer: Code Review Agent\\n> Verdict: APPROVE (with suggestions)\\n\\n## Scope\\n\\nThis review covers the uncommitted refactoring of `cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go` (replacing `FlattenTree`/`BuildTreeFromEntries` with `UpdateSubtree`), the new `checkpoint.CreateCommit` extraction in `committed.go` / `temporary.go`, the new `ShardParts()` method on `trail.ID`, and associated tests. The review is focused specifically on efficiency: unnecessary work, missed concurrency, TOCTOU, memory, and overly broad operations.\\n\\n## Previous Review Status\\n\\n- [ ] Issue from review-01 #1: `createCommit` useless wrapper -- STILL OUTSTANDING (still present in working copy)\\n- [ ] Issue from review-01 #2: `verifyTrailExists` duplicates navigation from `readCheckpointsFromTree` -- STILL OUTSTANDING (discussed further below)\\n- [ ] Issue from review-01 #4: Commit+ref-update pattern repeated 4 times -- STILL OUTSTANDING\\n- [ ] Issue from review-01 #5: `trail.ID` duplicates `checkpoint/id.CheckpointID` -- STILL OUTSTANDING\\n\\n---\\n\\n## New Findings\\n\\n### Finding 1: `Delete` calls `verifyTrailExists` then `UpdateSubtree` -- TOCTOU and duplicated reads\\n\\n**Severity:** Suggestion (not worth fixing now)\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:411-458` (`Delete`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:461-482` (`verifyTrailExists`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/parse_tree.go:51-118` (`UpdateSubtree`)\\n\\n**Analysis:** `verifyTrailExists` reads `rootTree -> shardTree -> trailEntry` (3 `TreeObject` calls + 2 `FindEntry` calls). Then `UpdateSubtree` with `pathSegments: []string{shard}` reads `rootTree` again (line 66 of `parse_tree.go`) and recurses into `buildLeafTree` which reads `shardTree` again (line 135). So the rootTree and shardTree are each read twice.\\n\\nIs this TOCTOU? Technically yes -- another process could update the branch ref between `verifyTrailExists` and `UpdateSubtree`. But this is a local-only single-process operation on an orphan branch. There is no realistic concurrent writer. And if there were, the TOCTOU window also exists between `getBranchRef` and `SetReference` at the end of every method (no compare-and-swap). So the `verifyTrailExists` TOCTOU is not a new class of bug.\\n\\nCould the existence check be eliminated? Not cleanly. If the trail does not exist, `UpdateSubtree` with `MergeKeepExisting` and `DeleteNames: []string{suffix}` silently succeeds (the suffix simply is not found in the shard tree's entries, so nothing is deleted). This would create a no-op commit -- functionally harmless but wastes a git object and produces a misleading \\\"Delete trail\\\" commit. The existence check is needed for the user-facing error.\\n\\n**Are the duplicate tree reads expensive?** go-git v5 uses an LRU object cache (`cache.NewObjectLRUDefault()`, 96MB default) on the filesystem storer. The `TreeObject(hash)` call goes through `storer.EncodedObject(plumbing.TreeObject, hash)` which checks the cache first. These tree objects are small (a few hundred bytes for shard directories). On second access within the same process, they will be served from the LRU cache. The cost is a cache lookup + object decode, not a filesystem read.\\n\\n**Verdict:** Not worth fixing. The duplicate reads are cache-served. The existence check serves a real purpose (user error reporting). If you want to eliminate the duplication purely for code quality, the `navigateToTrailTree` helper from review-01 finding #2 would help -- but that is a code-reuse concern, not a performance concern.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 2: `AddCheckpoint` calls `EnsureBranch` + `getBranchRef` -- two ref lookups\\n\\n**Severity:** Low (not worth fixing)\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:297-356` (`AddCheckpoint`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:39-63` (`EnsureBranch`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:486-504` (`getBranchRef`)\\n\\n**Analysis:** `AddCheckpoint` calls `EnsureBranch()` (which does `repo.Reference(refName, true)` at line 41) and then `getBranchRef()` (which does `repo.Reference(refName, true)` again at line 488). That is two reference lookups for the same ref.\\n\\n`EnsureBranch` returns early (`return nil`) when the branch exists (the 99%+ case). It does not return the reference it resolved. So `getBranchRef` must re-resolve it.\\n\\nCould they share the lookup? Yes, but it would require changing `EnsureBranch` to return `(plumbing.Hash, plumbing.Hash, error)` or to accept a callback, which complicates the API for other callers (`Write` also calls `EnsureBranch`). Alternatively, `AddCheckpoint` could skip `EnsureBranch` entirely since the trail must already exist for `AddCheckpoint` to make sense (you cannot add a checkpoint to a nonexistent trail). But defensively calling `EnsureBranch` prevents a confusing error if the branch was deleted externally.\\n\\n**Cost:** A git ref lookup is a filesystem `stat` + small file read (or packed-ref scan). Negligible for a CLI operation. On the happy path this is ~1 microsecond of overhead.\\n\\n**Verdict:** Not worth the API churn. The extra ref lookup is negligible. If you do the `commitAndUpdateRef` refactor from review-01 finding #4, consider having it accept an optional pre-resolved ref, but that is a design choice, not a performance requirement.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 3: `readCheckpointsFromTree` and `verifyTrailExists` duplicate tree walks -- cached by go-git\\n\\n**Severity:** Informational (no action needed)\\n\\nAs noted in finding #1, go-git uses an LRU object cache. The question \\\"does go-git cache `TreeObject` lookups?\\\" is answered: **yes**, via `cache.NewObjectLRUDefault()`. The cache operates at the `EncodedObject` level, so any object (tree, blob, commit) fetched once is cached for subsequent lookups by the same hash. The only exception would be if the cache is under extreme memory pressure (96MB limit), which is not realistic for the tiny tree objects involved here.\\n\\nBoth `readCheckpointsFromTree` and `verifyTrailExists` traverse rootTree -> shardTree -> trailTree. If both were called for the same trail (which does not currently happen -- `Delete` calls `verifyTrailExists` and `AddCheckpoint` calls `readCheckpointsFromTree`), the second traversal would be entirely cache-served.\\n\\n**Verdict:** No action needed. The concern was valid to raise, but go-git's caching eliminates the practical impact.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 4: `Write` always calls `EnsureBranch` even when the branch already exists\\n\\n**Severity:** Low (not worth fixing)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:72`\\n\\n**Analysis:** `Write` calls `EnsureBranch()` on every invocation. On the happy path (branch exists), `EnsureBranch` does one `repo.Reference()` call and returns. This is a single ref lookup (~1 stat + small read). For a CLI write operation that involves marshalling JSON, creating blob objects, building trees, and creating a commit, this overhead is negligible (likely <1% of total execution time).\\n\\nThe alternative would be to have callers check first, or to have `Write` skip the check when called from `Update` (which already read successfully, proving the branch exists). But this adds complexity and coupling for no measurable benefit.\\n\\n**Verdict:** Not worth fixing. Defensive idempotency checks are good practice for operations that create infrastructure on first use.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 5: `json.MarshalIndent` vs `json.Marshal` for git-stored blobs\\n\\n**Severity:** Suggestion (marginal, but worth considering)\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:135` (`buildTrailEntries`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:324` (`AddCheckpoint`)\\n\\n**Analysis:** `buildTrailEntries` uses `json.MarshalIndent(f.data, \\\"\\\", \\\"  \\\")` for all three trail files (metadata.json, discussion.json, checkpoints.json). `AddCheckpoint` also uses `MarshalIndent` when re-serializing checkpoints.json.\\n\\nFor a typical trail metadata JSON (~500 bytes compact), `MarshalIndent` produces ~700 bytes due to whitespace. The overhead is:\\n- **CPU:** `MarshalIndent` is ~20-30% slower than `Marshal` (it calls `Marshal` internally and then formats).\\n- **Storage:** ~40% more bytes per blob. With content-addressable storage, identical blobs are deduplicated, so unchanged files cost nothing extra. But every change creates a new blob that is 40% larger.\\n- **Git pack efficiency:** Whitespace actually _helps_ delta compression slightly (more common byte sequences). But the base object is larger.\\n\\nThese blobs _are_ occasionally human-read via `git show entire/trails:ab/cdef123456/metadata.json` or similar debugging. Pretty-printed JSON is significantly easier to read in that context.\\n\\n**Verdict:** Keep `MarshalIndent`. The readability benefit for debugging and manual inspection outweighs the marginal CPU and storage overhead. This is not a hot path. If the checkpoints list grows very large (hundreds of entries), compact JSON for `checkpoints.json` specifically would be worth reconsidering, but that is a future concern.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 6: Prepend pattern in `AddCheckpoint` (append + copy)\\n\\n**Severity:** Informational (no action needed)\\n\\n**File:** `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/trail/store.go:318-321`\\n\\n```go\\ncheckpoints.Checkpoints = append(checkpoints.Checkpoints, CheckpointRef{})\\ncopy(checkpoints.Checkpoints[1:], checkpoints.Checkpoints[:len(checkpoints.Checkpoints)-1])\\ncheckpoints.Checkpoints[0] = ref\\n```\\n\\nThis is a standard Go prepend idiom. For a slice of N elements:\\n- `append` may allocate a new backing array if capacity is insufficient (amortized O(1))\\n- `copy` shifts N elements right by one position (O(N))\\n- Total: O(N) time, O(N) memory\\n\\nFor realistic trail sizes (tens to low hundreds of checkpoints), this is trivially fast. The CheckpointRef struct is small (~120 bytes: three strings + a `time.Time`), so even 1000 elements would shift ~120KB -- well under a millisecond.\\n\\nAn alternative would be `slices.Insert(checkpoints.Checkpoints, 0, ref)` (Go 1.21+) which does the same thing internally but is more readable. However, that is a code quality suggestion, not a performance concern.\\n\\n**Verdict:** No action needed. The pattern is efficient for the expected data sizes.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 7: `CreateCommit` extraction in `committed.go` is a clean refactor\\n\\n**Severity:** Praise\\n\\n**Files:**\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/committed.go:1531-1562` (new `CreateCommit`)\\n- `/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/cli/cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/temporary.go:766` (delegating `createCommit`)\\n\\nThe extraction of `CreateCommit` as a package-level function is a clean refactor. The new function has the exact same implementation as the old method-level `createCommit`, and `temporary.go`'s method now delegates to it. No behavioral change, no efficiency impact, enables code reuse from the trail package.\\n\\n---\\n\\n### Finding 8: The overall refactoring from `FlattenTree` to `UpdateSubtree` is a significant efficiency improvement\\n\\n**Severity:** Praise\\n\\n**Context:** The committed (pre-refactor) version of `store.go` used `getBranchEntries()` which calls `FlattenTree` to recursively read the entire tree into a flat `map[string]object.TreeEntry`. This meant that `Write`, `Delete`, and `AddCheckpoint` all:\\n1. Read every blob path in the entire trails branch (O(total files across all trails))\\n2. Mutated the flat map\\n3. Rebuilt the entire tree from scratch via `BuildTreeFromEntries`\\n\\nThe refactored version uses `UpdateSubtree` which:\\n1. Reads only the tree nodes along the path to the target trail (O(depth) = O(2) for shard/suffix)\\n2. Replaces only the modified subtree\\n3. Preserves sibling entries by hash reference (no re-reading)\\n\\nFor `AddCheckpoint` specifically, the old version called `Read` (which reads all 3 files) then `Write` (which re-writes all 3 files). The new version reads only `checkpoints.json` and writes only `checkpoints.json` using `MergeKeepExisting`. This is a meaningful improvement as the number of trails grows.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Summary\\n\\n| # | Finding | Severity | Worth Fixing? |\\n|---|---------|----------|---------------|\\n| 1 | `Delete` TOCTOU: `verifyTrailExists` + `UpdateSubtree` double-reads | Suggestion | No -- cache-served, existence check needed for user error |\\n| 2 | `AddCheckpoint`: `EnsureBranch` + `getBranchRef` double ref lookup | Low | No -- ~1us overhead, API simplicity wins |\\n| 3 | Duplicate tree walks across `readCheckpointsFromTree`/`verifyTrailExists` | Informational | No -- go-git LRU cache handles it |\\n| 4 | `Write` always calls `EnsureBranch` | Low | No -- defensive idempotency is good practice |\\n| 5 | `json.MarshalIndent` vs `json.Marshal` for blobs | Suggestion | No -- readability for debugging outweighs marginal overhead |\\n| 6 | Prepend pattern in `AddCheckpoint` | Informational | No -- O(N) for small N, standard idiom |\\n| 7 | `CreateCommit` extraction | Praise | N/A |\\n| 8 | `FlattenTree` -> `UpdateSubtree` refactor | Praise | N/A -- this IS the fix |\\n\\n**Overall assessment:** APPROVE. The refactoring from `FlattenTree`/`BuildTreeFromEntries` to `UpdateSubtree` is the key efficiency improvement in this diff, and it is well-implemented. The six specific concerns raised in the review request are all either cache-mitigated, negligible-cost, or serve a necessary purpose (user error reporting). None warrant changes.\\n\\nThe outstanding issues from review-01 (code duplication of `verifyTrailExists` / `readCheckpointsFromTree` navigation, the `commitAndUpdateRef` pattern, and the `trail.ID` / `checkpoint/id.CheckpointID` duplication) remain relevant as code quality concerns but are orthogonal to efficiency.\\n\\n**Estimated effort to address feedback:** 0 hours (no changes recommended from an efficiency perspective).\\n\"},\"caller\":{\"type\":\"direct\"}}],\"stop_reason\":null,\"stop_sequence\":null,\"usage\":{\"input_tokens\":1,\"cache_creation_input_tokens\":393,\"cache_read_input_tokens\":89736,\"cache_creation\":{\"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens\":0,\"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens\":393},\"output_tokens\":25,\"service_tier\":\"standard\",\"inference_geo\":\"not_available\"},\"context_management\":null},\"requestId\":\"req_011CYgKmvQkpyQfLrsQMxcqt\",\"uuid\":\"3d305993-8523-4ee2-b0f5-ee67dce97090\"},\"normalizedMessages\":[],\